font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> produce enough potash to satisfy the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK demand, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the company </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only suppl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> about half this market with the remainder being imported from Germany, Russia and Canada.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Consequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> export large tonnages of potash to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some European customers as well as competing for sales worldwide.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to access the potash ore deposit, permanent roadways </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are mined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in underlying salt (Halite (95% NaCl)) producing about 800 ktpa of co-product that is mostly sold to local authorities and highway authorities as de-icing salt. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In recent years a new access r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oadway </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has been driven </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">into the underlying polyhalite seam and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the only mine in the world producing this mineral </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has a value as a fertiliser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mineral.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL contrib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">utes £225M per year economic activity as measured by product sales</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and much more by other economic measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Much of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> vendor spend is local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> supporting many small suppliers and service companies.  Half </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the company’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sales are overseas with approximate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">foreign earnings of £100M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">+</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> per year.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">How does the UK based extractive industries support employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citizens overseas? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> employ approximately 900 persons in high quality jobs, a further 150 full time contract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> employ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> work at the mine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, totalling over 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">050 persons. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All direct employees are employed at our Boulby Mine </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> nearby export terminal on the river Tees. A socio-economic study of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> impact suggested and confirmed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the mine s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">upport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> approximately 4,000 up-stream and down-stream jobs with a predominantly regional impact.  At any one time, the equivalent of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hree</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> full time employees are travelling the world for meetings with parent company, suppliers, customers, trade bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, conferenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es and other representations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s position as a centre for extractive industries i.e. In sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">note </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the decline of the UK extracti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve industry means that the UK is no longer a centre for extractive industries.  The decline of mining and quarrying activities has had a knock-on effect with a decline in UK suppliers of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">essential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">products such as mining machinery and day to day equipment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that increasingly have to be sourced outside the UK and even outside Europe. </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses overseas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitive position in this sector?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Not at all. Increa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">singly the expertise for extractive industry in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has been retired or made redundant or unemployed so that it has become difficult</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if not impossible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to recruit suitably qualified personnel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from this country. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hose mining companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have working mines in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have almost all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">taken over by foreign owned companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that are quoted on markets other than London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">K? Are there reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK has reputational risk because of the cost driven quality of their environmental impact assessments for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their operations.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The knowledge b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ase of the financial institutions needs to be much greater so they can understand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the complex </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technical and environmental issues rather than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ïve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> superficial knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL has many interactions with the NGO sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">take great </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pride in the high level of local and regional knowledge and understanding of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the mine’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> operations as we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ll as the very low level of objections to new or renewed licence applications.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although not the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">NGO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, CPL at its Boulby Mine is hosting an increasingly internationally significant range of research activities that utilises the ultra-low radiation ba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ckground to be found in the mine as well as its great depth (1,100m) which attenuates solar radiation by a factor 106.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ave hosted the STFC funded UK Dark Matter search since 1985 but recently the range of activities  have been expanded under the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">STFC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Futures Programme to include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">impact of cosmic rays on atmospheric aerosol formation, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development of muon tomography as an aid to carbon capture and storage technology, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">research into halophilic bacteria and archaea  and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">utilisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the mine as a Martian analogue for development of techniques and equipment for discovering life on Mars.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is in addition to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the company’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">own long term joint research project with Durham University investigating mining subsidence and coastal eros</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion and the range of natural and anthropomorphic influences upon this important natural phenomenon.  Cost effective methods of wide area monitoring have been investigated and models constructed of the mechanisms for cliff recession that have worldwide impl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ications. Recent additional interest in this unique research space has the potential to widen the scope of research even further with implications for UK plc Intellectual Property and that may bring additional benefits for underground operations worldwide.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">No – the skills base for the extractive industry worldwide is diminishing with the UK seemingly setting the lead in that decline. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are finding it increasingly difficult to recruit suitably qualified persons in the UK and increa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">singly applicants for mana</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> positions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are from mining areas in other parts of the world with Commonwealth and European countries predominating.  Technical positions are increasingly attracting applicants from those mining areas of Europe that are contracting through re-structu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ring.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although most of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mining staff are “home grown” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over 400 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">staff </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with 25 year long-service awards and several with 40 year service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> awards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the company </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recently recruited several miners from a UK coal mine that was closing, in advance of the n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eed for such staff.  This allows the opportunity to re-train them in potash mining techniques in time for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> needs.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increasingly difficult to recruit “green miners” locally and regionally.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CPL has no objections or comments regarding shale gas op</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erations but would like to draw the Select Committee’s attention to the possibility that shale gas operations have the potential to compromise working mines. This may happen by injudicious opening of faults and fractures that could possibly act as conduits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for gas or liquids to enter mine workings that hitherto were immune from such activity.  There is a strong case that shale gas and fracking operations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should not take place within 10km of working mines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (although this distance could be reduced if better kn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">owledge about the shale gas operation and its impact on the existing mine workings was available)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What is the impact of the industry of the UK signing up to the EITI?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EITI has absolutely no impact on CPL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">operations that exceed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the EITI criteria </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> position as a player in the global mining industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK signing up to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EITI is welcome.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excelle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nce for best practice and corporate governance?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some London listed companies are exemplars of environmentally acceptable mining operations around the world, others are less so.</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Cen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tury and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Extractive industry outputs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increasingly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">becoming international commodities and indigenous industries are being bought up by foreign companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seeking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">global market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">positions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Increasingly foreign ownership spells </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uncertainty for the UK operations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that can be reduced by more government support to this sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">David Pybus, External Affairs Manager.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.iclfertilizers.com/Fertilizers/ClevelandPotash/Pages/BUHomepage.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.iclfertilizers.com/Fertilizers/ClevelandPotash/Pages/BUHomepage.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.polysulphate.com/index.php"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.polysulphate.com/index.php</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>